<div id="review_1910932864" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1910932864" />
    <a title="BAM Endlessly Booked" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6595648-bam-endlessly-booked"><img alt="BAM Endlessly Booked" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1606603427p2/6595648.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1910932864?book_show_action=true">Apr 02, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="BAM Endlessly Booked" class="user" itemprop="url" name="BAM Endlessly Booked" href="/user/show/6595648-bam-endlessly-booked">BAM Endlessly Booked</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6595648-bam-endlessly-booked?shelf=audiobooks">audiobooks</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6595648-bam-endlessly-booked?shelf=library">library</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6595648-bam-endlessly-booked?shelf=classic-literature">classic-literature</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1910932864" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16572518587444712619">I don&apos;t agree with the main sentiment in this book. There IS nobility in death, in dying for principles, for those who are weaker.<br/><br/>Having said that, I was still moved by the frustration and disability of the main character. His strong desire to live and his poignant acceptance of loss were communicated not only literally but also figuratively through his flashbacks to happier times in his life, to the terms before the war and his body&apos;s destruction. <br/><br/>The author takes a passive stance toward battle</span>
  <span id="freeText16572518587444712619" style="display:none">I don't agree with the main sentiment in this book. There IS nobility in death, in dying for principles, for those who are weaker.<br /><br />Having said that, I was still moved by the frustration and disability of the main character. His strong desire to live and his poignant acceptance of loss were communicated not only literally but also figuratively through his flashbacks to happier times in his life, to the terms before the war and his body's destruction. <br /><br />The author takes a passive stance toward battle and those young men who go to fight and face their demise. There is fear, incredulity, denial, but most volunteer bravely to uphold the principles of our nation. I did not agree with the argument of <br />"America being just as free as Australia or Canada" at all. In fact I had to turn off the book for a few minutes while I debated, I was so upset. It's not the same at all. <br />The book definitely did its job at stirring up thought and discussion. It seems to go out of print when its ideals become unpopular to the government. I'm glad I got to see the other side of the argument.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16572518587444712619" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


